aleurod_aleyrodoidea	<br>\r\nWhen compared with the aphids (Aphidoidea) and scale insect groups (Coccoidea), whiteflies (Aleyrodoidea) living today appear to be a much less species-rich assemblage. The present collation has resulted in some 1556 available species names, in comparison with over 4500 aphidoids (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=476'>Remaudière & Remaudière, 1997</A>; <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=459'>Blackman & Eastop, 2006</A>) and over 7000 coccoids (<A HREF='http://\r\nwww.sel.barc.usda.gov/scalenet/scalenet.htm'>Miller & Ben Dov, 2003</A>). This apparent paucity of species is unlikely to reflect reality, however. Whiteflies have suffered from a particularly problematical systematic history (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=226'>Martin, 2003</A>), which has undoubtedly diverted the attentions of many systematists elsewhere. In particular over a century of taxonomy based almost solely on the final nymphal (“puparial”) stage, with many characters untested for their importance and significance, has not encouraged more systematists to become involved with the group.<p>\r\n(Extract from: <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=515'>Martin & Mound, 2007</A>)	<br>\r\nWhen compared with the aphids (Aphidoidea) and scale insect groups (Coccoidea), whiteflies (Aleyrodoidea) living today appear to be a much less species-rich assemblage. The present collation has resulted in some 1556 available species names, in comparison with over 4500 aphidoids (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=476'>Remaudière & Remaudière, 1997</A>; <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=459'>Blackman & Eastop, 2006</A>) and over 7000 coccoids (<A HREF='http://\r\nwww.sel.barc.usda.gov/scalenet/scalenet.htm'>Miller & Ben Dov, 2003</A>). This apparent paucity of species is unlikely to reflect reality, however. Whiteflies have suffered from a particularly problematical systematic history (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=226'>Martin, 2003</A>), which has undoubtedly diverted the attentions of many systematists elsewhere. In particular over a century of taxonomy based almost solely on the final nymphal (“puparial”) stage, with many characters untested for their importance and significance, has not encouraged more systematists to become involved with the group.\r\n<p>\r\n(Extract from: <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=515'>Martin & Mound, 2007</A>)	<br>\r\nSi comparados a los áfidos (Aphidoidea) y insectos del grupo de las cochinillas (Coccoidea), las moscas blancas (Aleyrodoidea) hoy vivientes\r\nparecen ser un grupo mucho menos rico en especies. La presente compilación resultó en unos 1556 nombres específicos, en comparación con más de 4500 de afidóideos (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=476'>Remaudière & Remaudière, 1997</A>; <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=459'>Blackman & Eastop, 2006</A>) y más de 7000 cochinillas (<A HREF='http://\r\nwww.sel.barc.usda.gov/scalenet/scalenet.htm'>Miller & Ben Dov, 2003</A>). Sin embargo, esa aparente pobreza en especies probablemente no reflite la realidad. Las moscas blancas sufrieron una história taxonómica particularmente problemática (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=226'>Martin, 2003</A>), que sin embargo ha alajdo las atenciones de los sistematas de este grupo. En particular, más de un siglo de taxonomía basado solamente en la fase ninfal final  (« puparial »), con muchos caracteres no testados cuánto a su importancia y significancia, no ha dado ánimo para aque más sistematas se enrollen con el grupo. <p>\r\n(Extract from: <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=515'>Martin & Mound, 2007</A>)\r\n\r\n\r\n	<br>\r\nComparadas aos afídeos (Afidoidea) e cochonilhas (Coccoidea), as moscas brancas (Aleyrodoidea) viventes aparentam ser um grupo bem menos rico em espécies. A presente compilação resultou em apenas 1556 nomes específicos disponíveis, em conparação com mais de 4500 afídeos \r\n (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=476'>Remaudière & Remaudière, 1997</A>; <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=459'>Blackman & Eastop, 2006</A>) e mais de 7000 cochonilhas (<A HREF='http://\r\nwww.sel.barc.usda.gov/scalenet/scalenet.htm'>Miller & Ben Dov, 2003</A>). \r\nNo entanto, esta aparente escassez de espécies provavelmente não reflete a realidade. As moscas brancas tem uma história taxonômica particularmente problemática, (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=226'>Martin, 2003</A>), o que, sem dúvida, desviou a atenção de muitos sistematas para outros grupos. Em especial, mais de um século de taxonomia baseada quase somente no último estágio ninfal ("pupário"), com muitos caracteres não testados quanto a sua importância e significância, não ajudaram a encorajar sistematas a se envolverem com o grupo.<p>\r\n(Extract from: <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=515'>Martin & Mound, 2007</A>)	<br>\r\nWhen compared with the aphids (Aphidoidea) and scale insect groups (Coccoidea), whiteflies (Aleyrodoidea) living today appear to be a much less species-rich assemblage. The present collation has resulted in some 1556 available species names, in comparison with over 4500 aphidoids (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=476'>Remaudière & Remaudière, 1997</A>; <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=459'>Blackman & Eastop, 2006</A>) and over 7000 coccoids (<A HREF='http://\r\nwww.sel.barc.usda.gov/scalenet/scalenet.htm'>Miller & Ben Dov, 2003</A>). This apparent paucity of species is unlikely to reflect reality, however. Whiteflies have suffered from a particularly problematical systematic history (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=226'>Martin, 2003</A>), which has undoubtedly diverted the attentions of many systematists elsewhere. In particular over a century of taxonomy based almost solely on the final nymphal (“puparial”) stage, with many characters untested for their importance and significance, has not encouraged more systematists to become involved with the group.<p>\r\n(Extract from: <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=515'>Martin & Mound, 2007</A>)	ouvrard	2012-05-03	bourgoin	2014-02-06	<br>\r\nWhen compared with the aphids (Aphidoidea) and scale insect groups (Coccoidea), whiteflies (Aleyrodoidea) living today appear to be a much less species-rich assemblage. The present collation has resulted in some 1556 available species names, in comparison with over 4500 aphidoids (<A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=476'>Remaudière & Remaudière, 1997</A>; <A HREF='http://www.hemiptera-databases.org/whiteflies/?db=aleurodes&lang=en&card=publication&id=459'>Blackman & Eastop, 2006</A>) and over 7000 coccoids (<A HREF='http://\r\nwww.sel.barc.usda.gov/scalenet/scalenet.htm'>Miller & Ben Dov, 2003</A>). This apparent paucity of species is unlikely to reflect reality, however. Whiteflies have s