inc_age	<script language="javascript">\r\nmenu('open');\r\n</script>\r\n<div id="<?php print($page); ?>">\r\n<p>Les premiers Cercopoidea, Procercopoidea sont connus du d&eacute;but du Jurassique &agrave; la fin du cr&eacute;tac&eacute;. La famille &eacute;teinte des Cercopionidae est elle connue de calcaires br&eacute;siliens datant de 110-115 millions d&apos;ann&eacute;es (d&eacute;but du cr&eacute;tac&eacute;) (Grimaldi, 2005). Les Ipsviciidae sont connus uniquement du Trias sup&eacute;rieur du Queensland. Selon Evans (1963), cette famille se place parmi les Cercopoidea.</p>\r\n<p>Quelques repr&eacute;sentants des familles Aphrophoridae et Cercopidae sont connus de l'ambre de la Baltique (Szwedo, 2002). Selon Grimaldi (2005), des Clastopteridae sont connus du Tertiaire et des Cercopidae se trouvent dans de l&apos;&eacute;oc&egrave;ne tardif du Colorado Florissant.</p>\r\n</div>	<script language="javascript">\r\nmenu('open');\r\n</script>\r\n<div id="<?php print($page); ?>">\r\n<p>The earliest Cercopoidea are Procercopoidae (Early Jurassic to Late Cretaceous); and the extinct family Cercopionidae is known from Early Cretaceous limestone of Brazil, between 110 to 115 million years old (Grimaldi, 2005). The Ipsviciidae, that have been recorded only from Upper Triassic strata in Queensland belong to the superfamily Cercopoidea according to Evans (1963).</p>\r\n<p>Repesentatives of Cercopidae and Aphrophoridae are recorded from Baltic amber, between 30 to 45 million years old (Szwedo, 2002). According to Grimaldi (2005) some Clastopteridae are known from the Tertiary and Cercopidae are found in the Late Eocene of Florissant, Colorado. </p>\r\n</div>	<script language="javascript">\r\nmenu('open');\r\n</script>\r\n<div id="<?php print($page); ?>">\r\n<p>Cercopoidea m&aacute;s temprano es Procercopoidae (Temprano Jurassic a Tard&iacute;o Cret&aacute;ceo); y conocen la familia extinta Cercopionidae de la Temprana caliza Cret&aacute;cea de Brasil, entre 110 a 115 millones de a&ntilde;os (Grimaldi, 2005).El Ipsviciidae, que ha sido registrado s&oacute;lo de estratos Superiores Triassic en Queensland pertenece a la superfamilia Cercopoidea seg&uacute;n Evans (1963). </p>\r\n<p>Repesentatives de Cercopidae y Aphrophoridae son registrados del &aacute;mbar b&aacute;ltico, entre 30 a 45 millones de a&ntilde;os (Szwedo, 2002). Seg&uacute;n Grimaldi (2005) conocen alg&uacute;n Clastopteridae del Terciario y Cercopidae es encontrado en el Tard&iacute;o Eoceno de Florissant, Colorado.</p>\r\n</div>	<script language="javascript">\r\nmenu('open');\r\n</script>\r\n<div id="<?php print($page); ?>">\r\n<p>Os Cercopoidea mais antigos são os Procercopoidae (Jurássico inferior a Cretáceo superior); e a extinta família Cercopionidae é conhecida de calcários brasileiros do Cretáceo inferior, com entre 110 a 115 milhões de anos (Grimaldi, 2005). Os Ipsviciidae, dos quais só há registros a partir do estrato Triássico Superior em Queensland, pertencem à superfamília Cercopoidea, de acordo com Evans (1963).</p>\r\n<p>Representantes de Cercopidae e Aprhophoridae foram encontrados em âmbar báltico, com entre 30 a 45 milhões de anos (Szwedo, 2002). De acordo com Grimaldi (2005) alguns Clastopteridae são conhecidos do Terciário e Cercopidae são encontrados no Eoceno Superior de Florissant, Colorado.\r\n</p>\r\n</div>\r\n	<script language="javascript">\r\nmenu('open');\r\n</script>\r\n<div id="<?php print($page); ?>">\r\n<p>The earliest Cercopoidea are Procercopoidae (Early Jurassic to Late Cretaceous); and the extinct family Cercopionidae is known from Early Cretaceous limestone of Brazil, between 110 to 115 million years old (Grimaldi, 2005). The Ipsviciidae, that have been recorded only from Upper Triassic strata in Queensland belong to the superfamily Cercopoidea according to Evans (1963).</p>\r\n<p>Repesentatives of Cercopidae and Aphrophoridae are recorded from Baltic amber, between 30 to 45 million years old (Szwedo, 2002). According to Grimaldi (2005) some Clastopteridae are known from the Tertiary and Cercopidae are found in the Late Eocene of Florissant, Colorado. </p>\r\n</div>	soulier	2011-04-14	bourgoin	2014-02-04	<script language="javascript">\r\nmenu('open');\r\n</script>\r\n<div id="<?php print($page); ?>">\r\n<p>The earliest Cercopoidea are Procercopoidae (Early Jurassic to Late Cretaceous); and the extinct family Cercopionidae is known from Early Cretaceous limestone of Brazil, between 110 to 115 million years old (Grimaldi, 2005). The Ipsviciidae, that have been recorded only from Upper Triassic strata in Queensland belong to the superfamily Cercopoidea according to Evans (1963).</p>\r\n<p>Repesentatives of Cercopidae and Aphrophoridae are recorded from Baltic amber, between 30 to 45 million years old (Szwedo, 2002). According to Grimaldi (2005) some Clastopteridae are known from the Tertiary and Cercopidae are found in the Late Eocene of Florissant, Colorado. </p>\r\n</div>
